<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2008-07-23T19:14:32-07:00</updated>
<published>2008-07-23T19:14:32-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4246&amp;p=35216#p35216</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4246&amp;p=35216#p35216"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Nestopia or Nintendulator, Do Either emulate Bus Conflicts?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4246&amp;p=35216#p35216"><![CDATA[
Bus conflict avoidance is one 74HC02 chip to disable the ROM during writes. This chip was the only difference between <a href="http://nesdevwiki.org/index.php/AxROM" class="postlink">AMROM and ANROM</a>. WRAM is two chips: a 6264 RAM and <a href="http://nesdevwiki.org/index.php/PRG_RAM_circuit" class="postlink">kyuusaku's 74HC10 based decoder</a>. But granted, chips weren't cheap as chips in the classic era.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Jul 23, 2008 7:14 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
